This Vignette written as an R Markdown Notebook provides a simple example of importing FACS data from different machines, annotating the samples and visualizing the results.

The data are generated using the three FACS machines used in NYU CGSB gencore

  1. Accuri
  2. Aria
  3. Cytek

1 Example Data

Below are the data that are used in this vignette. To work through this analysis:

  1. Download all directories and files from here
  2. Organize directories with the following structure.

You can see that there are three different directories /Accuri , /Aria and /Cytek that contain different .fcs files and samplesheets

2 Load required libraries

Several packages are required for running this analysis. If they are not installed, you need to run the following commands the first time:

2.1 Install Libraries

This workflow uses a variety of Bioconductor packages that should be loaded using: BiocManager::install() as per these guidelines.

#if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))
#    install.packages("BiocManager")
#BiocManager::install()
#BiocManager::install(ncdfFlow)
#BiocManager::install(flowCore)
#BiocManager::install(flowViz)
#BiocManager::install(ggcyto)
#BiocManager::install(ggforce)


#install.packages(tidyverse)
#install.packages(ggridges)

2.2 Loading the Gresham Lab’s flowtools from github

#install.packages(devtools)
#devtools::install_github("greshamlab/flowtools")

2.3 Load libraries

This workflow using the following packages (include linkes to vignettes using packages)

  • flowCore, which provides several functions for reading and manipulating .fcs files.
  • ncdfFlow, which reads .fcs files to disk rather than memory. This allows import of larger datasets as they do not need to be stored in memory.
  • ggcyto
    • basic functions
    • autoplot
    • visualize flowset
    • visualize gatingset

3.2 Assign sample names and other metadata

Information about the flowset is stored in an AnnotatedDataFrame. The dataframe

sampleNames(flowData) <- SampleSheet$Strain

pData(flowData)$Well <- SampleSheet$Well
pData(flowData)$Strain <- SampleSheet$Strain
pData(flowData)$Genotype <- SampleSheet$Genotype
pData(flowData)$Ploidy <- SampleSheet$Ploidy
pData(flowData)$Media <- SampleSheet$Media

3.4 Visualization using the ggcyto package

3.4.1 Using Autoplot

autoplot() is a simple function that provides quick plots of the data with minimal control on the appearance of the plot

3.4.1.1 Ploting a single channel

autoplot(flowData, "FL1.A") + scale_x_flowjo_biexp()

3.4.1.2 Plotting two channels

autoplot(flowData, "FSC.A", "FL1.A") + scale_x_flowjo_biexp() + scale_y_flowjo_biexp()

3.4.2 Using the ggcyto function

ggcyto provides more control over the plot

3.4.2.1 Ploting a single channel

p <- ggcyto(flowData, aes(x = FL1.A))
p + geom_density()

   #    + geom_hex(bins = 128) 
      # + geom_gate("CD8")

3.4.2.2 Using ggridges

p + scale_x_logicle() + geom_density_ridges(aes(y = Strain)) + facet_null() #facet_null is used to remove the default facet_wrap (by 'name' column)

3.4.2.3 2D Scatter plots

p <- ggcyto(flowData, aes(x = `FSC.A`, y =  `FL1.A`))
There were 12 warnings (use warnings() to see them)
p + geom_hex(bins = 128)
